		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/07/opinion/nyto-brazil/nyto-brazil-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/07/opinion/nyto-brazil/nyto-brazil-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/07/opinion/nyto-brazil/nyto-brazil-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003162821" width="592" height="586" alt=""   /><meta itemprop="height" content="586"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Miguel Schincariol/Agence France-Presse â Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//op-talk.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/10/08/what-an-election-year-looks-like-in-brazil/" data-title="What an Election Year Looks Like in Brazil" data-description="A pro-business, conservative candidate in Brazil&#039;s presidential election has surprised the country by upsetting a favored leftist challenger to President Dilma Rousseff.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âPresidentÂ <a style="color: #326891;" title="Times topic." href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/r/dilma_rousseff/index.html?8qa&amp;module=Search&amp;mabReward=relbias%3Aw%2C{%221%22%3A%22RI%3A7%22}">Dilma Rousseff</a>Â emerged on Sunday as the front-runner in one of the <a href="//google.com.br/elections/explorer#/election/br.2014/contest/1">most tightly contested presidential elections</a> since democracy was re-established in Brazil in the 1980s,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/10/06/world/americas/brazil-presidential-elections.html">reports</a> Simon Romero for The New York Times. However, âshe failed to win a majority of the vote, opening the way for a runoff with AÃ©cio Neves, the pro-business scion of a powerful political family.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Whatâs so special about this election? Well, whoever wins will be running what was, until recently, âLatin Americaâs colossus,â <a href="//www.bloombergview.com/quicktake/brazils-highs-lows">according toÂ David Biller of Bloomberg View</a>. âBrazilâsÂ <span style="color: #333340;">economic growth has slowed to its weakest three-year pace in a decade, advancing just 2.1 percent on average from 2011 through 2013,â he explains. âIn the first half of 2014, it entered technicalÂ recession. The currency has fallen 33 percent since President Dilma Rousseff rose to power in 2011. Business confidence in July reached the lowest level in more than a decade. Sovereign debt wasÂ downgraded<a style="color: #00b9e7;" href="//www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-03-24/brazil-s-credit-rating-cut-to-bbb-by-s-p-on-sluggish-growth.html">Â </a>on March 24 for the first time in that period.â</span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Any hope for economic recovery rests heavily on the shoulders of Brazilâs next president.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This heightens the stakes for Ms. Rousseff, whose opponent, Mr. Neves, has built a campaign platform on pro-business, pro-economic growth policies. Ms. Rousseffâs Workers Party, critics say, has stalled the countryâs once meteoric rise through a combination of âtax burden, the bureaucracy and steep tariffs.â Reducing these would âboost investment,â Mr. Biller reports, while âmore flexible labor laws would improve productivityâ â all hallmarkâs of Mr. Nevesâs campaign.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A campaign many observers did not think would survive as long as it has. Until recently, Mr. Neves trailed third in polls â far behind Ms. Rousseff and Marina Silva, of the Socialist Party. Ms. Silva, an Afro-Brazilian environmentalist from the poor, far-western state of Acre, was expected to give Ms. Rousseff a run for her money. As Jeffrey W. Rubin <a href="//blogs.reuters.com/great-debate/2014/10/03/brazils-elections-are-a-wake-up-call-to-for-its-business-community-the-country-is-moving-ahead-with-or-without-them/">wrote</a> for Reuters a few days before the election: âThe face of power in Brazil is becoming ever more diverse. The top twoÂ <span style="color: #000000;">candidates in Brazilâs presidential race on Sunday are both leftists and women, one of whom is black,â and continued, Â âthe private sectorâs preferred candidate, a white man from Brazilâs once-dominant center-right party, trails in the polls.â </span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span style="color: #000000;">Had Ms. Silva and Ms. Rousseff emerged neck and neck, the subsequent runoff would be a choice between âcompeting progressive agendas,â leaving the countryâs industrialist subsetÂ âwithout a serious contender for the first time since the countryâs transition to democracy in 1985.â</span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But Mr. Neves âpulled off a surprise second-place finishâ <a href="//www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-10-05/neves-to-face-rousseff-in-brazil-in-surprise-comeback.html">report</a> Raymond Colitt, Anna Edgerton and Blake Schmidt for Bloomberg News, perhaps because Brazilian voters are looking for ânew bloodâ for the presidential PalÃ¡cio do Planalto in BrasÃ­lia â and choosing between two socialist candidates may have proven an insufficient divergence.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ms. Rousseff herself cameÂ into office after her mentor and predecessor, Luiz InÃ¡cio Lula da Silva, enjoyed sky-high approval ratings nationwide. His administration maintained an economy averaging â4.1 percent annual growth,â becoming the worldâs second largest market after China.Â <span style="color: #2d2b2c;">âIt remains early days, but the likelihood that elections might prove to be the trigger for the much-needed shift in policy needed to revive Brazilâs flagging economy is at least greater than a few weeks ago,âÂ said Neil Shearing, the chief emerging markets economist at Capital Economics, told Bloomberg.</span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Another explanation for Mr. Nevesâs upset surge among voters is pure politics and image. â<span style="color: #4a4a4a;">In the campaignâs closing days Mr. Neves visited more than a dozen cities, twice as many as Ms. Silva,â The Economist <a href="//www.economist.com/news/americas/21622767-president-dilma-rousseff-enters-election-day-handsome-lead-battle-second-place-too">reports</a>. âHe has withstood the campaignâs hardships well. On October 2nd, during the last televised debate before the first round, he exuded a mix of poise and swagger, taking Ms. Rousseff to task over a kickback scandal involving Petrobras, the state-controlled oil giant mismanaged on Ms. Rousseffâs watch. Ms. Silva, fragile-looking as it is, appeared visibly tired. So did Ms. Rousseff, who two days later rasped at a press conference that she would not be answering any questions because she was on the cusp of losing her voice.â</span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And finally, there is the pragmatistâs perspective. Voters rejected Ms. Silva because, while her ascent story is inspiring, she may have been perceived asÂ underqualified or ill-prepared for the countryâs top job. âMarina is emotion. Dilma is reason,â <a href="//www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/03/dilma-rousseff-election-brazil-vote-president">said</a> Professor GaudÃªncio Torquato, a professor of political communications at the University of SÃ£o Paulo, in an interview with The Guardian. âMarina embodies the opposition to old-style politics. Dilma represents the continuation of <em>bolsa familiaÂ </em>â wallet full, fridge full, tummy full, a grateful heart and head. This is what determines how people vote.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">â<span style="color: #4a4a4a;">When the time comes to cast ballots Brazilians tend to play it safe,â <a href="//www.economist.com/news/americas/21622767-president-dilma-rousseff-enters-election-day-handsome-lead-battle-second-place-too">says</a> The Economist. âRomance seldom prevails. Life, after all, is not aÂ </span><em style="color: #4a4a4a;">telenovela</em><span style="color: #4a4a4a;">.âÂ </span></p>
